name: Dothraki
description:
Introduction

Unique cross-joint in the Navajo sandstone layer featuring a plethora of rappels, a handful of challenging downclimbs, and a brief, very tight narrows section. This route is a good option for the experienced group if you are looking for a dry canyon that does not require a permit in the Zion area.

Dothraki is not to be underestimated! This is a challenging canyon for someone not used to stemming and tough downclimbs.

Approach

Two options here, both seem to take the same amount of time; around 3hrs to 1st anchor.

Squirrel Canyon TH (no shuttle)

This is the original approach starting from Squirrel Canyon TH which does not require a shuttle. This approach has about 600 feet of elevation gain up semi steep sandy road and use trails to the cliff band then follows up a ravine through the cliff band gaining an additional 450 feet with a few sections of very steep sand and loose rock. Take your time while navigating this section. Once at the top of the ravine you will be on a ridge known locally as the Dragon's Back which you then scramble and walk all the way up to the head of the canyon with great views over the area. The route up the ravine to the Dragon's Back has a couple of portions that are difficult to describe in words. Be ready to do a little route finding in a couple short sections.

Water Canyon TH (10min shuttle)

This approach is said to be easier than the original with less aggressive terrain but more mileage. Park a vehicle at Squirrel Canyon TH and shuttle down to Water Canyon TH. Follow the very obvious, well used, Water Canyon trail up to Top Rock, then begin cross country travel across mostly open desert with a few easy grades.

Descent

R1: 85' tree LDC

Downclimb very slippery slanted ledge LDC or spicy drop off on RDC. Meat anchor/partner assist can be helpful here.

Downclimb steep slope shortly after, LDC

R2: 15' small oak LDC or spicy downclimb

R3: 150' bolts LDC

R4: 30' bolts RDC

Enter long very tight narrows section requiring stemming.

R5: 55' bolts RDC

Begin long walk to next anchor with another stemming downclimb 1/4 of the way.

R6: 70' bolts LDC, exposed

R7: 20' bolts

R8: 60' bolts LDC

R9: 30' tree RDC up high (very loose soil/rock)

Downclimb 10' drop using crack in LDC wall shortly after R8

R10: 40' tree, head high

R11: 35' bolts LDC

R12: 12' bolts LDC

R13: 25' bolts LDC

R14: 25' bush LDC, up high

R15: 20' rock pinch

R16: 15' bush RDC, (rappel over large wedged boulders)

R17: 130' bolts LDC, down to canyon floor (or 30' down to bolts LDC and 100' down to canyon floor)

Exit

Follow drainage a short ways down climbing a few short drops for about 250' until you can exit RDC up steep loose sand to the trail above. Another 400' down the trail crosses another steep drainage and continues on the other side. Eventually meet up with sandy 4x4 trail that would be part of the original approach trail and follow it down to Squirrel Canyon TH.

Red tape

Beta Sites

  • https://www.bluugnome.com/cyn_route/zion/zion_dothraki/zion_dothraki.aspx
  • https://www.stavislost.com/hikes/trail/dothraki-canyon

Trip reports and media

I have now done this canyon twice. We went with 8 people on the water canyon approach and the time in was spot on(I did the chute the last time and it is really no fun but the dragons back is super cool)

There are many spicy down climbs that you may or may not be comfortable with. If you go have plenty of webbing and know how to set up an anchor. Some of the webbing was questionable and had to be replaced. But overall a very fun day. Getting rescued out of this canyon would be extremely difficult.

Our group was too big and not every person had the same level of experience so it took us 10 hours to do the technical portion of the canyon. Plan accordingly!

Background

Many new bolt stations have been installed by SAR on 10/21/2018, following a 15 hour rescue mission
